    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Machaeranthera bigelovii are typically derived from its leaves and stems, which are rich in flavonoids and terpenoids, and are used to make tea by infusing 1-2 teaspoons of dried herb in 1 cup of boiling water for 5-10 minutes. A tincture can be prepared by steeping 1 part herb in 2-3 parts solvent, such as ethanol or glycerin, for 2-4 weeks and then straining and filtering the mixture. An infusion is similar to tea but typically requires a larger amount of herb and can be used as a topical application or taken internally. A salve can be made by infusing the herb in a carrier oil, such as olive or coconut oil, and then mixing it with beeswax to create a semi-solid topical application. An infused oil can be prepared by steeping the herb in a carrier oil for 2-6 weeks, which can be used as a topical application or added to skin care products.",
